flowRoot.flowPara: A Service is a named collection of methods that can be called remotely by a Client.
To define a Service, create a new somata.Service, passing the name and a map of method names to functions.
When run, the Service will choose a random port number and register itself with the local Registry agent, then start listening on that port for method calls from Clients.
A Client can connect and send messages to Services to call methods remotely.
To create a Client, just initialize a new somata.Client. The Client will connect to the local Registry agent and will then be prepared to make requests.
To call methods from a remote Service, use the Client's remote method. Specify the name of the Service, name of the method, a set of arguments, and a callback.

In the background, the client asks the Registry about how to connect to this Service (the host and port combination), creates a socket to connect to the Service (storing it for subsequent calls to this Service) and then sends a JSON message over the socket with the method name and arguments.
When the Client receives a response from the Service, the callback will be called with either an error or the successful response data.
